This is a great question about V8's implementation details! The key difference lies in how these two methods handle their arguments internally.

## The Problem with `push(...hugeArray)`

When you use the spread operator with `push`, you're essentially doing this:

```javascript
array.push(hugeArray[0], hugeArray[1], hugeArray[2], ..., hugeArray[n])
```

This translates to a function call with potentially millions of arguments. V8 (and most JavaScript engines) have a limit on the number of arguments that can be passed to a function, which is tied to the call stack size.

Here's what happens under the hood:

1. The spread operator expands the array into individual arguments
2. Each argument needs to be pushed onto the call stack
3. The call stack has a finite size (typically around 10,000-50,000 frames)
4. When you exceed this limit, you get "Maximum call stack size exceeded"

```javascript
// This will crash with a large array
const hugeArray = new Array(1000000).fill(1);
const array = [];
array.push(...hugeArray); // RangeError: Maximum call stack size exceeded
```

## Why `concat` Works

`concat` is implemented differently in V8. It doesn't use the JavaScript call stack for processing array elements. Instead, it:

1. Creates a new array
2. Iterates through the elements using internal C++ loops
3. Copies elements directly in memory without function call overhead

Here's a simplified view of how V8 implements these methods:

```javascript
// Conceptual implementation of push with spread
Array.prototype.push = function(...items) {
    // Each item is an individual argument on the call stack
    for (let i = 0; i < items.length; i++) {
        this[this.length] = items[i];
    }
    return this.length;
}

// Conceptual implementation of concat
Array.prototype.concat = function(...arrays) {
    const result = new Array();
    // Copy this array first
    for (let i = 0; i < this.length; i++) {
        result[i] = this[i];
    }
    // Then process each array argument
    for (const arr of arrays) {
        // This loop runs in native code, not on JS call stack
        for (let i = 0; i < arr.length; i++) {
            result[result.length] = arr[i];
        }
    }
    return result;
}
```

## Practical Solutions

If you need to add many elements to an array, here are better approaches:

```javascript
// 1. Use concat (creates a new array)
array = array.concat(hugeArray);

// 2. Use a loop (modifies existing array)
for (const item of hugeArray) {
    array.push(item);
}

// 3. Use push with apply and chunking for very large arrays
const chunkSize = 10000;
for (let i = 0; i < hugeArray.length; i += chunkSize) {
    array.push.apply(array, hugeArray.slice(i, i + chunkSize));
}

// 4. Set length and copy manually (fastest for large arrays)
const startLength = array.length;
array.length = startLength + hugeArray.length;
for (let i = 0; i < hugeArray.length; i++) {
    array[startLength + i] = hugeArray[i];
}
```

## Performance Comparison

Here's a simple benchmark to illustrate the differences:

```javascript
const sizes = [1000, 10000, 100000];

sizes.forEach(size => {
    const hugeArray = new Array(size).fill(1);

    // Concat - always works
    console.time(`concat ${size}`);
    let arr1 = [].concat(hugeArray);
    console.timeEnd(`concat ${size}`);

    // Push with spread - will fail on large sizes
    try {
        console.time(`push spread ${size}`);
        let arr2 = [];
        arr2.push(...hugeArray);
        console.timeEnd(`push spread ${size}`);
    } catch (e) {
        console.log(`push spread ${size}: Failed - ${e.message}`);
    }

    // Loop push - always works but slower
    console.time(`loop push ${size}`);
    let arr3 = [];
    for (const item of hugeArray) {
        arr3.push(item);
    }
    console.timeEnd(`loop push ${size}`);
});
```

The key takeaway is that `concat` processes arrays at the native level without using the JavaScript call stack for each element, while the spread operator with `push` creates a function call with all array elements as individual arguments, quickly exhausting the call stack with large arrays.
